    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2058590739" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2058590739" />
    <a title="Matthew Cole" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21219251-matthew-cole"><img alt="Matthew Cole" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1519926963p2/21219251.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2058590739?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Cole" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Cole" href="/user/show/21219251-matthew-cole">Matthew Cole</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780345349286" href="/book/show/1666.On_Heroes_and_Tombs">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21219251-matthew-cole?shelf=2017">2017</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2058590739" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16615441920729546433">This is for the most part a philosophical novel about the tortuous nature of love and the impenetrability of loved ones. It&apos;s related through conversations between two friends as they attempt to piece together memories of their dead lovers, but the story is also interlaced with Argentine history - a history of battles and radical ideas. At its core the novel is about a man&apos;s search for meaning in a cruel, senseless world.<br/><br/>All of that stuff is good, but the real treat in the book comes in the thir</span>
  <span id="freeText16615441920729546433" style="display:none">This is for the most part a philosophical novel about the tortuous nature of love and the impenetrability of loved ones. It's related through conversations between two friends as they attempt to piece together memories of their dead lovers, but the story is also interlaced with Argentine history - a history of battles and radical ideas. At its core the novel is about a man's search for meaning in a cruel, senseless world.<br /><br />All of that stuff is good, but the real treat in the book comes in the third of its four parts, in a so-called 'Report on the Blind', which is a first-person account of a man's investigation into a clandestine sect of blind people that controls society. That is, according to his testimony. Here the novel shifts into full-on psychological thriller mode, and for me it recalled something of the obsessive madness found in Poe's 'A Telltale Heart' - the narrators in both texts are fanatical in their attention to detail, and make repeated appeals to the reader by professing to the veracity of their accounts, as well as to their own sanity. Sabato's novel contains the more disturbing and otherworldly imagery, however, and keeps you in a limbo between believing the magical conspiracy offered on the one hand, and dismissing the conspiracy as dream and hallucination on the other. (Chris Nolan's film The Prestige teases the viewer in a similar way; it isn't clear whether the world of the film obeys the laws of physics, or whether it is subject to disruption by magic.)<br /><br />Sabato organises the novel in a strange way, or it might be truer to say he leaves it disorganised. The disparate discussions, histories, and philosophical musings are deeply connected to each other, but there isn't a guiding narrative thread that unequivocally answers the mystery that binds them together. Sabato mentioned that his own lack of clarity in his philosophical obsessions was borne out in the text, but I didn't mind the lack of closure when I reached the end; firstly because the book never led me to expect answers, and secondly because in the place of answers Sabato sets down a simple, peaceful, and elegant final thought that saves humanity from its need for certainty.<br /><br />Kind of. Ha.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16615441920729546433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


