    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2322009172?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Milica Modrá" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Milica Modrá" href="/user/show/52147074-milica-modr">Milica Modrá</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780345349286" href="/book/show/1666.On_Heroes_and_Tombs">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52147074-milica-modr?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2322009172" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8450589538926685371">I&apos;m not really sure how do you review a book that has no faults, other than just pointing it out that the book doesn&apos;t have faults.<br/>I really enjoyed this book. What I like about it is that it has a lot of smaller underline stories going on during the main story, and they all paint a better picture of what life was like in Buenos Aires and they give you a deeper understanding of the characters. These stories might be boring to some people, but that&apos;s the deal, you can chose if you want to make the</span>
  <span id="freeText8450589538926685371" style="display:none">I'm not really sure how do you review a book that has no faults, other than just pointing it out that the book doesn't have faults.<br />I really enjoyed this book. What I like about it is that it has a lot of smaller underline stories going on during the main story, and they all paint a better picture of what life was like in Buenos Aires and they give you a deeper understanding of the characters. These stories might be boring to some people, but that's the deal, you can chose if you want to make them important to you or not. You can still understand the main story if you choose not to give all these smaller ones importance (but I recommend you that you read everything with focus and concentration, only because it will make the whole novel more colorful and interesting). I loved following the relationship of Alejandra and Martin, the way of Sabato's writing just left me hungry for more and more, I couldn't put the book down, I was always curious to find out what was going to happen and expected some key revelation at times that will make everything fall into place.<br />Although the ending might not be what I expected (and I'm not even sure what I was expecting), I really love it anyway. This book opened a lot of questions for me and changed my perspective on life</span>
  <a data-text-id="8450589538926685371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


