<div id="review_3883255662" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3883255662" />
    <a title="Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52482799-thomas"><img alt="Thomas" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3883255662?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas" href="/user/show/52482799-thomas">Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780345349286" href="/book/show/1666.On_Heroes_and_Tombs">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3883255662" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7348253777267597568">As soon as I began Heroes and Tombs I was transported back to reading The Tunnel nearly 20 years ago, a book that enthralled me at the time. Sabato whips up that same dark, romantic atmosphere in the opening scenes. Martin, a hopeless, foppish, love-struck young man, tells of his encounter with the alluring Alejandra in a park in Buenos Aires and his subsequent obsession with finding her. Their affair immediately has an air of doomed inevitability, just like the poor painter in The Tunnel who si</span>
  <span id="freeText7348253777267597568" style="display:none">As soon as I began Heroes and Tombs I was transported back to reading The Tunnel nearly 20 years ago, a book that enthralled me at the time. Sabato whips up that same dark, romantic atmosphere in the opening scenes. Martin, a hopeless, foppish, love-struck young man, tells of his encounter with the alluring Alejandra in a park in Buenos Aires and his subsequent obsession with finding her. Their affair immediately has an air of doomed inevitability, just like the poor painter in The Tunnel who simply has to understand what the woman "saw" in his painting, consequences be damned. While Sabato conjures up his own dark, mysterious, brooding, doomed Buenos Aires, he is also not the most original of stylists. Unlike recent read, Clarice Lispector, who writes in a sphere of her own uniqueness, Sabato's writing is, for better or worse, resounding with echoes of others. He is a deeply intellectual writer and his influences are plain to see. Like The Tunnel, Heroes and Tombs initally feels like a cross between Kafka and Camus, but the more epic scope of the novel reveals a strong afinity with Dostoyevsky. This decrepid tale of elegant madness could have been written by the Russian great except for the brilliantly evoked shadows of Buenos Aires that haunt it.<br /><br />The first half of the book revolved around Martin and Alejandra's romance. While this held my interest for a while, mostly because of Alejandra's mysterious character) Martin quickly begins to get annoying. The suspense surrounding Alejandra's family and the certain knowledge that tragedy awaits poor Alejandra turns the book into something of a Dumas epic, with all of the Gothic trappings of The Count of Monte Christo and Dracula. Alejandra tells a good horror story or two, her sensuality brought out in Martin's sexual frustration and her obvious depression. Still, I was glad when the perspective changes at the midway point and Martin disappears from the story. Suddenly we find ourselves back in time, in the company of Alejandra's insane father, Fernando, who is obsessed with a theory that the blind control the world through a secret, underground Sect. He uses the a friend's blindness to attempt to infiltrate this organisation, descending deeper and deeper into madness. This section is deeply narcissistic and pessimistic. Fernando sees the human world as doomed and essentially evil. What follows is a masterpiece of suspense, as good as anything that Poe wrote and as crazily twisted as the dark workings of Lovecraft's imagination.<br /><br />The final quarter does not capitalise on this amazing build up of tension. Sabato deliberately frustrates us by refusing to reveal what we want to find out. Instead we are transported back into Fernando's childhood by the memories of Bruno, a childhood friend who loved Fernando's cousin and maintained a strange fascinating for Fernando. Bruno describes much more of the historical context and political activity of the time, the various anarchistic groups that struggled in an urban world fighting for a sense of liberty, while corrupt politicians repressed and crushed attempted revolutions. All the while the city goes on, eternal and ghostly. Dying slowly are the aristocratic, post-colonial old families like the Vidals. Bruno's stories give the Vidal family a further dusty sense of Gothic, tumbled down doom, and there are some haunting scenes led by the madness of Fernando, culminating in a spine tingling encounter with the mad old lady in the attic (every family needs one, Alejandra once says) as Bruno tries to sneak in and steal the mummified head she keeps by her bedside.<br /><br />Warped by unspoken incest, overshadowed by the fiery end of Alejandra and her father, Heroes and Tombs is a challenging and disturbing book from start to finish. In parts, particularly Fernando's Report on the Blind, it is gripping and awful, like the best psychological horror stories. But apart from the obvious overtones of madness, Sabato's novel is grounded in a realistic and politically charged Buenos Aires and the book is centred on the city's identity. A sense of crumbling history permeates the book, finishing as it does with frustrating flashbacks to General Lavalle - a distant relative of the Vidal family. The scope of Sabato's book sometimes distracts from what is good about it; the tension and the atmosphere, the Gormenghastian ruins of the rich and the insane, the surreal underworld of violence and murder. That's not to take away from the ambition of the book, but I preferred Sabato distilled into the powerful punch of The Tunnel. Heroes and Tombs makes you shiver, but its impact is lessened by the numerous distractions and by the weakness of important characters like Martin and Bruno, passive observers of the aristocratic drama unfolding tragically around them. 6</span>
  <a data-text-id="7348253777267597568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


